        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔍</span> Solver</a> <a href="/activities/#quiz" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎯</span> Quiz</a> <a href="/activities/#anagram" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔀</span> Anagram</a> <a href="/activities/#rack" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎲</span> Rack</a> <a href="/activities/#wotd" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">📖</span> WOTD</a> <a href="/sixty-seconds/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">⏱️</span> 60s</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Collins Scrabble Words (CSW) is the official published edition of the international Scrabble word list most players know as SOWPODS. Published by HarperCollins, it's the most comprehensive English-language Scrabble reference with 280,000+ entries — and it's the definitive authority for tournament play outside North America.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Collins and SOWPODS: The Same List</h2>
      <p>The first question most players ask: what's the difference between Collins Scrabble Words and SOWPODS? The answer is simple — they're the same word list under different names.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Name Relationship</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200"><span class="text-white font-medium">SOWPODS</span> is the informal player name. <span class="text-white font-medium">Collins Scrabble Words (CSW)</span> is the official published name. The word list is identical — CSW is simply what you buy in a bookshop or reference in tournament rules. Think of it like "tissues" vs "Kleenex" — same thing, different label.</p>
      </div>

      <p>When WESPA (World English-Language Scrabble Players Association) specifies the official dictionary for international tournaments, they reference "Collins Scrabble Words" — not "SOWPODS." But players universally use both names interchangeably, and no one will correct you in a Scrabble club for saying either.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">History of Collins Scrabble Words</h2>
      <p>The publishing partnership between HarperCollins and the Scrabble community has a rich history spanning several decades.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 CSW Publishing History</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">1980s:</strong> Chambers Dictionary provided the British word list (OSW). Collins was not yet involved.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">1991:</strong> First SOWPODS list compiled (merging OSW + TWL). HarperCollins begins publishing it.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">2007:</strong> Collins officially brands the list "Collins Scrabble Words" (CSW07). Regular update cycle begins.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">2019–2024:</strong> CSW19 and CSW24 editions add thousands of new words from modern English usage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>HarperCollins leverages their massive lexicographic database (the Collins Corpus, with over 20 billion words of text) to identify new entries. Words must show sustained usage in published sources before being added to CSW.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Updates and Editions</h2>

